arch:property.oc:show_val: L12 is fill north of the wall in L7. We opened this locus to separate the fill on both sides of the wall between L8 at the south and L12 at the north. We have expanded the locus to encompass all of the fill north of the wall to the edge of the first step. Adjacent to the center of the wall in L7 we found that ashy fill was continuing beneath the wall and changed locus. The surrounding fill is still L12. Because we extended L12 to the edge of the first step, it may be mixed with some subtopsoil fill that has eroded down the tepe, but we keep the KT bags from those areas separate from the rest.
plaster, ash, pottery, pebbles, animal burrows, mixed with some subtopsoil fill
compacted soil with lots of animal burrows probably mudbrick collapse mixed with subtopsoil fill

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
